fflere are three alternative explanations for the labellar “mandibles,” the most plausible being number 2. ffle first is that the male bites onto the oviscapt as a postcopulatory mate-guarding device. However, I know of no behavioral context in drosophilids from which this could have evolved. In insects, males would typically stay mounted or coupled while mate-guarding (
Alcock, 1994
). Second, the male may be attaching itself to the female while mounted, by biting, for example, onto her wing edge.
